# $Id$

Solaris scripts to control OpenDNSSEC processes:

Any package for solaris should probably include something like the following:

In the prototype:

...
i preremove
i postinstall
d none /lib/svc/method/OpenDNSSEC 0755 root root
d none /var/svc/manifest/application/OpenDNSSEC 0755 root root
d none /lib/svc/method/OpenDNSSEC/ods-signerd.init=ods-signerd.init 0555 root root
d none /lib/svc/method/OpenDNSSEC/ods-enforcerd.init=ods-enforcerd.init 0555 root root
f none /var/svc/manifest/application/OpenDNSSEC/ods-signerd-smf.xml=ods-signerd-smf.xml 0555 root root
f none /var/svc/manifest/application/OpenDNSSEC/ods-enforcerd-smf.xml=ods-enforcerd-smf.xml 0555 root root
...

In the preremove

...
/usr/sbin/svcadm disable ods-enforcerd
/usr/sbin/svccfg -v delete svc:/application/OpenDNSSEC/ods-enforcerd:default

/usr/sbin/svcadm disable ods-signerd
/usr/sbin/svccfg -v delete svc:/application/OpenDNSSEC/ods-signerd:default
...

In the postinstall

...
/usr/sbin/svccfg -v import /var/svc/manifest/application/OpenDNSSEC/ods-signerd-smf.xml
/usr/sbin/svccfg -v import /var/svc/manifest/application/OpenDNSSEC/ods-enforcerd-smf.xml
...


Then you can use:

svcadm [enable|disable] ods-signerd
svcadm [enable|disable] ods-enforcerd

to control the processes
